<DOC><DOCNO> AP890319-0030 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 1358EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Korea     03-19 0306</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Korea,0318</SECOND><HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0690 to fix garble in keyword.</HEAD><HEAD>Dissidents Call For President's Ouster, Removal of U.S. Troops</HEAD><HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL1</HEAD><BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Thousands of students and workerscheered calls Sunday by dissident leaders for the ouster ofPresident Roh Tae-woo and the immediate withdrawal of U.S. troopsfrom South Korea.   Leaders of the United National Democratic Movement, the maindissident alliance, told a rally of 5,000 people at HanyangUniversity that opposition forces must unite to defeat thegovernment in a pending national referendum.   ``Down with Roh Tae-woo!'' and ``Yankee go home!'' protesterschanted.   Some students hurled firebombs and rocks at riot police in abrief clash after the rally. Police fired volleys of tear gas thatdrove protesters back.   Thousands of riot police had surrounded the school, but there waslittle trouble after alliance leaders urged people to dispersepeacefully.   Police officials reported no arrests or injuries.   Alliance chairman Lee Bu-yong told the rally Roh was a front formilitary rule.   ``We cannot suffer any more under the Roh regime. We must oustthe Roh regime without fail,'' Lee said.   Paik Ki-wan, another leading dissident, denounced the UnitedStates for supporting the Roh government and charged Washington wastrying to control South Korea like a colony.   ``The real culprit is the United States,'' he said.   Protesters repeatedly called for the withdrawal of 42,000 U.S.troops based in South Korea. The United States has said they willremain as long as the South Korean government wants them.   Roh, a former general who won a presidential election in December1987, is expected this week to announce plans for a nationalreferendum on his performance as president.   The government says Roh will not step down if he is defeated.Some opposition groups are demanding he resign if defeated.</TEXT></DOC>